      <hedline>
        <hl1>Social Security: Are Stocks Safe?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Steve Buzbee, commenting on Gov George W Bush's Social Security reform plan, as outlined in Martin Feldstein's May 22 Op-Ed, says problem lies in occasional statistical aberration of full-blown stock market crash</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Martin Feldstein's defense of Gov. George W. Bush's Social Security reform plan (Op-Ed, May 22) seems to disregard the original rationale behind the creation of the Social Security system.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Martin Feldstein's defense of Gov. George W. Bush's Social Security reform plan (Op-Ed, May 22) seems to disregard the original rationale behind the creation of the Social Security system.</p>
        <p>Although average market returns do show better growth than the current system, the problem lies in the occasional statistical aberration of a full-blown stock market crash.</p>
        <p>Imagine the case of a retirement nest egg in the stock market for a person set to retire in 1930. No statistical averaging would have undone the financial harm that person would have experienced in the crash of '29.</p>
        <p>Now imagine that everyone in the country set to retire in that same year had held an equal stake in the market. The consequences would have been disastrous for the entire economy.</p>
        <p>Any safety net involving redistribution of assets into more stable investments during bear markets would serve only to accelerate any sell-off that might occur.</p>
        <p>STEVE BUZBEE  Highland Park, N.J., May 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
